    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nIf you have a Cython class that defines an `__eq__` method, and a second Cython class that inherits from the first and defines a `__hash__` method, then the equality operator inherited by the second class (i.e. `x == y`) breaks. Confusingly, calling the `__eq__` method directly gives the correct result (i.e. `x.__eq__(y)`). Removing the `__hash__` method from the second class fixes the equality operator.\n\nI also tried a few other special methods instead of `__hash__`, but it seems that `__hash__` is the only special method I could find that exhibits this behaviour. Further, it's not linked to what `__hash__` does, just the presence of it. This was tested by setting the `__hash__` method to either `return super().__hash__()` or `raise Exception`. In both cases, the equality operator breaks.\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\nfoobar module:\n\n```python\nimport cython\n\n@cython.cclass\nclass Foo:\n    _foo: int\n\n    def __init__(self, foo):\n        self._foo = foo\n\n    @property\n    def foo(self):\n        return self._foo\n\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        return isinstance(other, Foo) and self.foo == other.foo\n\n@cython.cclass\nclass Bar(Foo):\n    def __hash__(self): \n        return super().__hash__()  # Return identical values to not having a __hash__ method\n```\n\nPython script:\n\n```python\nimport foobar\n\nbar_a = Bar(1)\nbar_b = Bar(1)\n\nprint(bar_a == bar_b)  # True if foobar module is run under Python, False if foobar compiled under Cython\nprint(bar_a.__eq__(bar_b)) # True under both Python and Cython\n```\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\n`bar_a == bar_b` should ideally be the same under Python and Cython.\n\n### OS\n\nMacOS\n\n### Python version\n\n3.14\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.4\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I think this is how Python itself handles extension types:\n\nhttps://github.com/python/cpython/blob/4b3330813760a3e3c75cd03023d252742168683b/Objects/typeobject.c#L12276-L12282\n\nBased on your example, it looks like extension types and regular Python types behave a bit differently.\n\nMy view is that we probably shouldn't change this - extension types are special and don't always behave exactly like regular Python types. But I agree that it's a bit unexpected.",
